Note with concern that lack of access to appropriate, safe, effective and affordable antimicrobials and diagnostic tools, particularly in developing countries, is responsible for more deaths than antimicrobial resistance, while stressing that, in 2019, 4.95 million deaths were associated with drug-resistant bacterial infections, including 1.27 million deaths directly attributable to bacterial antimicrobial resistance, 20 per cent of whom were children under 5,
“Global burden of bacterial antimicrobial resistance in 2019: a systematic analysis”, The Lancet, vol. 399, No. 10325 (February 2022). and that without a stronger response there will be an estimated average loss of life expectancy of 1.8 years globally by 2035;
Global Leaders Group on Antimicrobial Resistance, “GLG report: Towards specific commitments and action in the response to antimicrobial resistance”.
